types.section:
{{fr-adv}}

# [[more than one knows what to do with]], [[more than one can shake a stick at]] {{gloss|a great number or amount of}}
#: {{uxi|fr|Les Mirabeau ont de l'argent '''à ne savoir qu'en faire'''|The Mirabeaus have '''more''' money '''than they know what to do with'''.}}

====Usage notes====
* The adverbial pronoun {{m|fr|en}} is sometimes placed after {{m|fr|ne}} instead of {{m|fr|que}}:
*: '''{{m|fr||à n'en savoir que faire}}'''
** With this word-order, the pronoun {{m|fr|que}} is sometimes replaced with {{m|fr|quoi}}:
**: '''{{m|fr||à n'en savoir quoi faire}}'''
* Though {{m|fr|savoir}} is one of the few French verbs that does not necessarily require the use of {{m|fr|pas}} along with {{m|fr|ne}} to be negated, it is quite common for it to be included in this locution:
*: '''{{m|fr||à ne pas savoir qu'en faire}}'''.
** Similarly, the quasi-negative element {{m|fr|plus}} is often added, with our without the shifting of {{m|fr|en}} mentioned above:
**: '''{{m|fr||à ne plus savoir qu'en faire}}'''
**: '''{{m|fr||à n'en plus savoir que faire}}'''
**: '''{{m|fr||à ne plus en savoir que faire}}'''
* Not to be confused with such phrases as:
*: {{m|fr|ne savoir que faire|ne (pas) savoir que faire}} / {{m|fr|ne savoir que faire|ne (pas) savoir quoi faire|t=to be undecided; or, to be crestfallen}}
*: {{m|fr|ne savoir que faire pour|ne (pas) savoir que faire pour|t=to have put all of one's resources toward a delicate undertaking}}
*: {{m|fr|ne savoir que faire de|ne (pas) savoir que faire de|t=to be embarrassed about; to find useless or have no use for}}
*: etc.
